# Cloudflare Access (multiagent.vision)

## Shared Service Token

**The same CF Access tokens are used for all services** behind Cloudflare Access:

- `cvat.multiagent.vision` (bs2 / Traefik)
- `mvat.multiagent.vision` (rke2 nginx Ingress — **requires DNS + tunnel**; see `infra/docs/MVAT_AND_CVAT_PARALLEL.md` if the hostname does not resolve)
- `clearml.multiagent.vision` / `clearml-api.multiagent.vision` / `clearml-files.multiagent.vision`
- `registry.multiagent.vision` (Harbor)
- `jenkins.multiagent.vision`
- Other `*.multiagent.vision` hosts on the same Access application


## Headers for Machine-to-Machine Access

Include these headers in HTTP requests when calling from outside the LAN (e.g. scripts, CI, external clients):

```
CF-Access-Client-Id: <CF_ACCESS_CLIENT_ID>
CF-Access-Client-Secret: <CF_ACCESS_CLIENT_SECRET>
```

## Examples for Machine-to-Machine Access

Use values from `cursor-context/secrets/cloudflare-access.env` (or your password manager). Do not commit real tokens.

```bash
# Export once per shell (example names — match your .env keys)
export CF_ACCESS_CLIENT_ID="<your-client-id>.access"
export CF_ACCESS_CLIENT_SECRET="<your-client-secret>"
export JENKINS_USER="admin"
export JENKINS_PASSWORD="<jenkins-admin-password>"

# CVAT — should return 200
curl -s -o /dev/null -w '%{http_code}' \
  -H "CF-Access-Client-Id: ${CF_ACCESS_CLIENT_ID}" \
  -H "CF-Access-Client-Secret: ${CF_ACCESS_CLIENT_SECRET}" \
  "https://cvat.multiagent.vision/api/server/about"

# MVAT — should return 200 (same service token as other *.multiagent.vision hosts)
curl -s -o /dev/null -w '%{http_code}' \
  -H "CF-Access-Client-Id: ${CF_ACCESS_CLIENT_ID}" \
  -H "CF-Access-Client-Secret: ${CF_ACCESS_CLIENT_SECRET}" \
  "https://mvat.multiagent.vision/api/server/about"

# ClearML API — should return 401 (needs ClearML auth, but CF Access passes)
curl -s -o /dev/null -w '%{http_code}' \
  -H "CF-Access-Client-Id: ${CF_ACCESS_CLIENT_ID}" \
  -H "CF-Access-Client-Secret: ${CF_ACCESS_CLIENT_SECRET}" \
  "https://clearml-api.multiagent.vision/auth.login"

# Jenkins — trigger build (crumb + build must share session via cookies)
CRUMB=$(curl -s -c /tmp/jc.txt -b /tmp/jc.txt -u "${JENKINS_USER}:${JENKINS_PASSWORD}" \
  -H "CF-Access-Client-Id: ${CF_ACCESS_CLIENT_ID}" \
  -H "CF-Access-Client-Secret: ${CF_ACCESS_CLIENT_SECRET}" \
  "https://jenkins.multiagent.vision/crumbIssuer/api/json" | python3 -c "import json,sys; print(json.load(sys.stdin)['crumb'])")
curl -s -b /tmp/jc.txt -u "${JENKINS_USER}:${JENKINS_PASSWORD}" \
  -H "CF-Access-Client-Id: ${CF_ACCESS_CLIENT_ID}" \
  -H "CF-Access-Client-Secret: ${CF_ACCESS_CLIENT_SECRET}" \
  -H "Jenkins-Crumb: $CRUMB" -X POST "https://jenkins.multiagent.vision/job/chessverse-monorepo/job/main/buildWithParameters"
```

**Jenkins crumb**: The crumb request and the build POST must share the same session. Use `-c` to save cookies, `-b` to send them. Without cookies, Jenkins returns 403 "No valid crumb".

## Token Location

- **Canonical**: `cursor-context/secrets/cloudflare-access.env` (gitignored) — copy from `cloudflare-access.env.example`, fill in.
- **Doc**: `EXTERNAL_ACCESS_CVAT_CLEARML.md` (or Downloads) — full examples for CVAT, ClearML, curl.
- **CVAT + MVAT parallel**: `infra/docs/MVAT_AND_CVAT_PARALLEL.md` — Cloudflare DNS/tunnel for `mvat.multiagent.vision`; `infra/scripts/check-cvat-mvat-public.sh` checks both APIs with this token.
- **CVAT browser "Cannot connect"** while `/api/server/about` + token returns 200: (1) **Disk on CVAT Docker host (bs2)**: if **`/` ≥ ~90% full**, `/api/server/health/?format=json&org=` returns **500** (django-health-check DiskUsage) and the SPA shows "Cannot connect" — SSH to host, `df -h /`, free space (`docker image prune -af`), re-test health locally. (2) **Cloudflare**: complete Access SSO; if still broken, WAF **Skip** for Super Bot Fight Mode on `cvat.multiagent.vision` — see `infra/docs/EXTERNAL_ACCESS_CVAT_CLEARML.md` (*CVAT web UI*). Full write-up: `lessons/troubleshooting-log.md` **[2026-03-28] CVAT UI "Cannot connect"**.

## Internal Access (No Tokens)

On the same LAN (e.g. k8s on bs1/bs3), use internal IPs — no Cloudflare, no tokens:

- CVAT: `http://10.0.0.5:8082`
- ClearML: `http://10.0.0.5:8008` / `:9080` / `:9081`

## Limitation: Docker/Kaniko

Docker registry clients (Kaniko, containerd, docker) **do not support custom headers**. They cannot send CF-Access-Client-Id/Secret. For in-cluster pushes to Harbor, use the internal registry: `harbor-registry.harbor.svc.cluster.local:5000`.

